 most prominent figures in the development of new music after World War II, he is renowned for both his compositions and his utopian views. His many essays and lectures reveal an artist at the center of the analytical, theoretical, critical, and political debates of the time. This selection of Nono’s most significant essays, articles, and interviews covers his entire career (1948–1989), faithfully mirroring the interests, orientations, continuities, and fractures of a complex and unique personality. His writings illuminate his intensive involvements with theatre, painting, literature, politics, science, and even mysticism. Nono’s words make vividly evident his restless quest for the transformative possibilities of a radical musical experience, one that is at the same time profoundly engaged with its performers and spaces, its audiences, and its human and social motivations and ramifications.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aMusicy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aMusicy20th century. 7aMUSIC / Individual Composer & Musician.2bisacsh  a20th century.  aarticles.  aartist.  aartistic.  abiographical.  acollected work.  acollection.  acomposer.  acompositions.  acontemporary artist.  acontemporary world.  acritical.  aessays.  afamous composer.  ainterviews.  alectures.  aliterature.  amusic.  amusician.  amysticism.  anew music.  anono.  anostalgia.  apainting.  aperformer.  apolitical.  apolitics.  apost war.  aradical.  ascience.  asingle author anthology.  atheatre.  atheoretical.  atheory.  atransformation.  autopian.  aworld war 2.  awwii.1 aDe Benedictis, Angela Ida, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRizzardi, Veniero, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook 